    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Death Penalty Debate</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>American Bar Association aide Elisabet</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 14 front-page article raises questions about whether a number of those executed in Texas were innocent. Fear of executing the innocent has prompted the first serious debate about the continued imposition of the death penalty since it was reinstated in 1976.</p>
        <p>The focus on innocence suggests that we can and should draw a line between those who are worthy of constitutional protections (the innocent) and those who are not (the guilty). While your article exposes the inadequacies of the legal process by which we decide who will live and who will die in Texas, the denial of fundamental fairness and due process plagues the administration of the death penalty throughout the country.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 14 front-page article raises questions about whether a number of those executed in Texas were innocent. Fear of executing the innocent has prompted the first serious debate about the continued imposition of the death penalty since it was reinstated in 1976.</p>
        <p>The focus on innocence suggests that we can and should draw a line between those who are worthy of constitutional protections (the innocent) and those who are not (the guilty). While your article exposes the inadequacies of the legal process by which we decide who will live and who will die in Texas, the denial of fundamental fairness and due process plagues the administration of the death penalty throughout the country.</p>
        <p>Unless concerns about the wrongfully convicted lead us to confront the larger failures of the capital punishment system, we will have only taken a detour on the long road to an American justice system that is ''equal under law.''</p>
        <p>ELISABETH SEMEL  Washington, May 15, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is director of the American Bar Association's Death Penalty Representation Project.</p>
      </block>
